snippet.textDisplay:
I've been painting vehicles since 92 (quit around 2008) and I can tell you those red colors are the devil. You will never get a color close enough to butt match, so you will have to blend. You said that the panels were two different colors, if they match each other then you put enough basecoat on so it was the wrong color.

There is also another problem and it is the factory doesn't put enough basecoat on and you are looking at the sealer through the basecoat. This makes matching impossible. My truck in my profile pic is a prime example of the factory not putting enough basecoat on. My gas lid is a different color than my bed, my mirrors and door handles are different from the doors. I bought a tonnea cover that needed to be painted and I went through 4 different paint lines and all of their variants trying to find my correct color. I found one that matches in the sunlight, but looks like crap under artificial lights. I've got a few dents I would like to fix but I would be more pissed about the color not matching than having the dents in the truck. Once the truck is paid for I will respray the entire truck with House of Kolor (because I could then butt match the color if I needed to later on).

snippet.textDisplay: If you got the correct paint code & your supplier mixed it correctly, it has to be too dark of a sealer. Reds almost always require either white or a light gray groundcoat, plus more than two coats are needed for coverage. Even with a dead nuts match I'd still blend the back door to be 100% sure. Reds are among the easiest to blend also, so this is really an easy fix.
snippet.textOriginal: If you got the correct paint code & your supplier mixed it correctly, it has to be too dark of a sealer. Reds almost always require either white or a light gray groundcoat, plus more than two coats are needed for coverage. Even with a dead nuts match I'd still blend the back door to be 100% sure. Reds are among the easiest to blend also, so this is really an easy fix.
